\chapter{Incremental label edits, the \texttt{cli.utils.labels}
module}%
\label{cli.utils.labels}

Both [[nytid todo edit]] and [[nytid track edit]] let the user adjust an
item's labels.  The blunt instrument is [[--label]]/[[-l]], which
\emph{replaces} the entire set; adding one label to an item that already
has five then means re-typing all six.  The finer instruments are
[[--add-label]]/[[-a]] and [[--remove-label]]/[[-r]], which adjust the
label set \emph{relative} to its current contents.

Both commands need the exact same merge rule, and the rule has enough
edge cases---contradictory requests, idempotent no-ops---that duplicating
it invites drift.  We therefore factor it into this single pure helper.
Keeping it free of any CLI or storage dependency lets both commands import
it and lets us test the rule without a CLI harness.

