``apply_label_edits`` to implement their ``--add-label``/``--remove-label``
flags. See the ``cli.utils.labels`` chapter in the manual for the design
rationale.
"""
<<the apply_label_edits function>>
@

\section{The [[apply_label_edits]] function}

The merge has one deliberate ordering decision: we remove first, then add.
The alternative---adding first---would let a request to both drop and
re-add the same label silently cancel out, hiding a likely mistake.  By
removing first we can instead detect that the same label appears in both
lists and reject the whole edit as a contradiction: the caller cannot
coherently mean both \enquote{drop this} and \enquote{keep this}.

A label that appears in both [[add]] and [[remove]] is therefore a hard
error ([[ValueError]]) for the command layer to turn into a non-zero exit.
The two softer cases---removing a label that is absent, or adding one that
is already present---are harmless and idempotent.  Failing on those would
make the flags unsafe to run repeatedly from automation, so instead we
record a warning and carry on, returning the warnings so the caller can
surface them on stderr while still succeeding.

<<the apply_label_edits function>>=
def apply_label_edits(current, add, remove):
    """Return (new_labels, warnings) after removing then adding.

    Starting from `current`, remove every label in `remove` and then
    append every label in `add` that is not already present.  Returns the
    resulting label list together with a list of human-readable warning
    strings for no-op removals and additions.

    Raises `ValueError` if a label appears in both `add` and `remove`.
    """
    conflict = set(add) & set(remove)
    if conflict:
        raise ValueError(
            "label(s) given to both --add-label and --remove-label: "
            + ", ".join(sorted(conflict)))
    warnings = []
    result = list(current)
    for lab in remove:
        if lab in result:
            result = [x for x in result if x != lab]
        else:
            warnings.append(
                f"label '{lab}' not present; nothing to remove")
    for lab in add:
        if lab in result:
            warnings.append(
                f"label '{lab}' already present; not added")
        else:
            result.append(lab)
    return result, warnings
@

\section{Tests}

Tests are tangled into [[tests/test_cliutilslabels.py]].  The function is
pure, so the tests need no fixtures: they pass label lists in and assert on
the returned list and warnings.

<<test [[cliutilslabels.py]]>>=
import sys
sys.path.insert(0, "../src")

import pytest

from nytid.cli.utils.labels import apply_label_edits

<<test functions>>
@

A successful edit removes first and then appends, so the kept labels stay
in their original order and the added one lands at the end.  (Both callers
normalize their own labels---[[TodoItem]] on assignment, [[TrackingEntry]] on
construction---so this helper does not sort.)

<<test functions>>=
def test_apply_label_edits_remove_then_add():
  result, warnings = apply_label_edits(
    ["draft", "DD1310"], ["urgent"], ["draft"])
  assert result == ["DD1310", "urgent"]
  assert warnings == []
@

Adding a label that is already present, or removing one that is absent, is
an idempotent no-op: the label set is unchanged and a warning explains why.
<<test functions>>=
def test_apply_label_edits_present_add_warns():
  result, warnings = apply_label_edits(
    ["DD1310"], ["DD1310"], [])
  assert result == ["DD1310"]
  assert any("already present" in w for w in warnings)


def test_apply_label_edits_absent_remove_warns():
  result, warnings = apply_label_edits(
    ["DD1310"], [], ["absent"])
  assert result == ["DD1310"]
  assert any("nothing to remove" in w for w in warnings)
@

A label requested in both [[add]] and [[remove]] is contradictory and
raises before any change is computed.
<<test functions>>=
def test_apply_label_edits_conflict_raises():
  with pytest.raises(ValueError):
    apply_label_edits(["DD1310"], ["x"], ["x"])
@
